In Table II, we compare the convergence performance of HierMo with benchmark algorithms. The numbers show the accuracy when different algorithms are run for T𝑇T iterations. The experiment is conducted on linear regression, logistic regression, CNN, VGG16, and ResNet18.
We set T=1000𝑇1000T=1000 (MNIST), T=4000𝑇4000T=4000 (UCI-HAR), or T=10000𝑇10000T=10000 (CIFAR10 and ImageNet), γ=0.5,γa=0.5formulae-sequence𝛾0.5subscript𝛾𝑎0.5\gamma=0.5,\gamma_{a}=0.5. There are 4 workers and 2 edge nodes with each edge node serving 2 workers (three-tier algorithm). There are 4 workers directly served by the cloud (two-tier algorithm).
For two-tier algorithms, we set τ=20𝜏20\tau=20 (convex model) or τ=40𝜏40\tau=40 (non-convex model). For three-tier algorithms, we set τ=10,π=2formulae-sequence𝜏10𝜋2\tau=10,\pi=2 (convex model) or τ=20,π=2formulae-sequence𝜏20𝜋2\tau=20,\pi=2 (non-convex model).
Please note that since π𝜋\pi does not exist for two-tier algorithms, we set τ𝜏\tau value for two-tier algorithms equal to τ​π𝜏𝜋\tau\pi value for three-tier algorithms for a fair comparison.
These hyper-parameters are typically used in existing works [13, 14, 22, 18, 8].

We also compare the training accuracy when more workers (N=50𝑁50N=50 and N=100𝑁100N=100) participate the training to demonstrate the cross-siloed FL [41] (typically up to one hundred participants). The results in Fig. 3(d) and (h) show the same trend as results in Table II.

We observe that HierMo >> HierFAVG >> DOMO >> FedADC >> FedNAG >> CFL >> FedMom >> SlowMo >> Mime ≈\approx FedAvg in most cases. This is consistent with the results in Table II, showing that HierMo outperforms all benchmarks under any levels of non-i.i.d. data distribution.
We also observe higher level of non-i.i.d. setting decreases convergence performance for all algorithms. Specifically, HierMo achieves 66.11% accuracy for high level non-i.i.d. data, while achieving 92.21% accuracy and 94.70% accuracy for middle and low level non-i.i.d. data respectively. This matches our expectations where higher level of non-i.i.d. setting causes more data divergence that is denoted by larger δ𝛿\delta, and therefore lowers the accuracy.
